quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to test the variable's value using the switch statement.
[!raw!]
int x = 10;
{0} ({1}) {
  case 10:
    System.out.println("A");
    break;
  {2} 20:
    System.out.println("B");
    break; 
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The switch Statement[/h1]

A [b]switch [/b]statement tests a variable for equality against a list of values. Each value is called a [b]case[/b], and the variable being switched on is checked for each case.
[b]Syntax:[/b] [code format="java" ][b]switch [/b](expression) {
   [b]case [/b]value1 :
     //Statements
     [b]break[/b]; //optional
   [b]case [/b]value2 :
     //Statements
     [b]break[/b]; //optional
    //You can have any number of case statements.
    [b]default [/b]: //Optional
       //Statements
}[/code]
- When the variable being switched on is equal to a [b]case[/b], the statements following that [b]case [/b]will execute until a [b]break [/b]statement is reached.
- When a [b]break [/b]statement is reached, the [b]switch [/b]terminates, and the flow of control jumps to the next line after the [b]switch [/b]statement.
- Not every [b]case [/b]needs to contain a [b]break[/b]. If no [b]break [/b]appears, the flow of control will fall through to subsequent cases until a [b]break [/b]is reached.

The example below tests [b]day [/b]against a set of values and prints a corresponding message. [code format="java" codeId="736"]int day = 3;

[b]switch[/b](day) {
  [b]case [/b]1:
    System.out.println("Monday");
    break;
  [b]case [/b]2:
    System.out.println("Tuesday");
    break;
  [b]case [/b]3:
    System.out.println("Wednesday");
    break;
}
// Outputs "Wednesday"[/code]
[note]You can have any number of [b]case [/b]statements within a [b]switch[/b]. Each [b]case [/b]is followed by the comparison value and a colon.[/note]

quizzes.question:
What is the output of the following code?
int a = 11; int b = 12; int c = 40;
switch (a) {
 case 40:
   System.out.println(b);
   break;
 default:
   System.out.println(c);
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]The default Statement[/h1]

A switch statement can have an optional [b]default [/b]case. 
The [b]default [/b]case can be used for performing a task when none of the cases is matched.
 
[b]For example:[/b] [code format="java" codeId="737"]int day = 3;

switch(day) {
  case 6:
    System.out.println("Saturday");
    break;
  case 7:
    System.out.println("Sunday");
    break;
 [b] default[/b]:
    System.out.println("Weekday");
}
// Outputs "Weekday"[/code]
[note]No [b]break [/b]is needed in the default case, as it is always the last statement in the switch. [/note]
